'''Woollyback''' is a dialect term used in [[Liverpool]], England for a non-Liverpudlian

The term usually refers to a person from the neighbouring towns of [[St Helens, Merseyside|St Helens]], [[Widnes]], [[Warrington]] and [[Wigan]], as these places each share a similar [[English English#Northern English|accent]] to each other, though substantially different from Liverpool's '[[scouse]]'. The term may also be used to simply refer to somebody that is not from Liverpool.  Originally it was a nickname for those people who worked on the [[:Category:Liverpool Docks|docks in Liverpool]], who used to carry the wool for export onto the ships and were therefore called 'woollybacks'. 

